WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.853 --> 00:00:03.742
<v ->This is a story that I believe will touch your heart</v>

2
00:00:03.742 --> 00:00:05.460
as much as it has ours.

3
00:00:05.460 --> 00:00:07.028
It's about a man who had reached a point

4
00:00:07.028 --> 00:00:09.694
of total despair and could see no way out.

5
00:00:09.694 --> 00:00:12.895
With his vision so narrowed and with no hope remaining,

6
00:00:12.895 --> 00:00:15.839
he made all of the proper preparations to end his life,

7
00:00:15.839 --> 00:00:17.685
when at the last hours,

8
00:00:17.685 --> 00:00:20.265
he logged on to our site looking for a miracle,

9
00:00:20.265 --> 00:00:22.077
and found it.

10
00:00:23.502 --> 00:00:27.473 line:15% 
(heartwarming music)

11
00:00:30.846 --> 00:00:33.407
Jeff, it's hard to believe you're the same person

12
00:00:33.407 --> 00:00:35.560
that walked into Lee's office a month ago

13
00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:37.448
ready to end it all.

14
00:00:37.448 --> 00:00:39.486
You're downright sparkling.

15
00:00:39.486 --> 00:00:41.567
What a shift.

16
00:00:41.567 --> 00:00:44.512
Let's just dig right in to the genesis

17
00:00:44.512 --> 00:00:46.764
of how you had found yourself there to begin with,

18
00:00:46.764 --> 00:00:48.406
and where this started in life

19
00:00:48.406 --> 00:00:49.943
because I think there an awful lot of people

20
00:00:49.943 --> 00:00:52.482
out there that have experienced the same feelings

21
00:00:52.482 --> 00:00:53.687
or do at this moment,

22
00:00:53.687 --> 00:00:57.462
and can take great inspiration from your words.

23
00:00:57.462 --> 00:00:59.209
So let's begin,

24
00:00:59.508 --> 00:01:02.338
at what point in your life did you start experiencing

25
00:01:02.338 --> 00:01:04.892
that kind of detachment or pain

26
00:01:04.892 --> 00:01:08.303
to where you really considered seriously ending your life?

27
00:01:08.303 --> 00:01:10.935
<v ->I think it began primarily as a teenager.</v>

28
00:01:10.935 --> 00:01:13.430
Teenage life is difficult in general,

29
00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:14.986
especially these days, I believe.

30
00:01:14.986 --> 00:01:19.223
But for a young, gay teenager it's even more difficult.

31
00:01:19.223 --> 00:01:21.318
I came to the realization, I think at age 13,

32
00:01:21.318 --> 00:01:22.534
that I was gay,

33
00:01:22.534 --> 00:01:24.446
and I lived in an environment that was not supportive

34
00:01:24.446 --> 00:01:25.542
whatsoever.

35
00:01:25.542 --> 00:01:28.507
I felt rejection from members of my family,

36
00:01:28.507 --> 00:01:30.914
rejection from friends at school,

37
00:01:30.914 --> 00:01:32.013
I felt isolated.

38
00:01:32.013 --> 00:01:34.668
I believed that I was the only gay person in our small town

39
00:01:34.668 --> 00:01:35.970
in Ohio,

40
00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:37.601
which today I know isn't true,

41
00:01:37.601 --> 00:01:40.545
but at the time I felt I was the only one,

42
00:01:40.545 --> 00:01:42.264
and it was a horrible depression.

43
00:01:42.264 --> 00:01:43.385
I'd come home from school

44
00:01:43.385 --> 00:01:45.246
and just sleep for hours and hours,

45
00:01:45.246 --> 00:01:47.422
and I would wanna think of ways that I could

46
00:01:47.422 --> 00:01:49.049
end the pain and end the depression

47
00:01:49.049 --> 00:01:50.884
because it was so painful.

48
00:01:50.884 --> 00:01:52.196
<v ->We were talking a little bit ago,</v>

49
00:01:52.196 --> 00:01:53.482
before the camera was rolling,

50
00:01:53.482 --> 00:01:56.078
about the whole notion of being gay and you had mentioned

51
00:01:56.078 --> 00:01:59.138
in passing, and we didn't follow up on it,

52
00:01:59.138 --> 00:02:02.478
it was interesting because gay goes beyond sexuality,

53
00:02:02.478 --> 00:02:03.398
<v ->Right.</v>

54
00:02:03.398 --> 00:02:04.421
<v ->And what did you mean by that?</v>

55
00:02:04.421 --> 00:02:07.659
<v ->Well being gay is not about sex necessarily.</v>

56
00:02:07.659 --> 00:02:10.955
I think being gay is really about accepting yourself

57
00:02:10.955 --> 00:02:15.093
and your position or orientation in life to other people.

58
00:02:15.093 --> 00:02:17.088
For the love that you feel for men

59
00:02:17.088 --> 00:02:18.475
and the love that you feel for women.

60
00:02:18.475 --> 00:02:21.327
Being gay doesn't mean that you do not love women.

61
00:02:21.327 --> 00:02:24.006
It's not a sexual issue in nature.

62
00:02:24.006 --> 00:02:26.907
I think it's much broader and very misunderstood

63
00:02:26.907 --> 00:02:28.991
by those who have never experienced what it is

64
00:02:28.991 --> 00:02:30.490
to be gay.

65
00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:32.809
And although a lot of people throughout my lifetime

66
00:02:32.809 --> 00:02:34.846
asked me, when did you choose to be gay?

67
00:02:34.846 --> 00:02:35.806
And I told 'em,

68
00:02:35.806 --> 00:02:37.860
well when did you choose to be straight?

69
00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:39.630
"I don't really know, I was always this way."

70
00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:41.439
Said, well it's the same with us.

71
00:02:41.439 --> 00:02:43.230
We've always been this way it's just a matter

72
00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:44.958
of when do you accept that,

73
00:02:44.958 --> 00:02:46.074
and move on.

74
00:02:46.074 --> 00:02:48.604
<v ->So how did your parents and family respond to you?</v>

75
00:02:48.604 --> 00:02:50.856
<v ->Well my mother surprisingly responded pretty well</v>

76
00:02:50.856 --> 00:02:54.333
by the time she knew, and that was probably in my early 30s

77
00:02:54.333 --> 00:02:55.376
when she found out.

78
00:02:55.376 --> 00:02:56.418
But of course as a mother she says,

79
00:02:56.418 --> 00:02:58.677
"Well I always knew there was something different about you,

80
00:02:58.677 --> 00:03:00.789
but I love you and accept you the way you are."

81
00:03:00.789 --> 00:03:03.456
But other members of my family,

82
00:03:03.456 --> 00:03:05.923
particularly those who are very religious,

83
00:03:05.923 --> 00:03:08.697
biblicly, as Christians,

84
00:03:09.259 --> 00:03:12.632
had a very difficult time accepting it and understanding it.

85
00:03:12.792 --> 00:03:14.846
It really affected our relationship to the point

86
00:03:14.846 --> 00:03:16.863
that we really don't talk that much,

87
00:03:16.863 --> 00:03:18.798
unfortunately.

88
00:03:18.798 --> 00:03:20.468
I'm hopeful that one day they'll come around

89
00:03:20.468 --> 00:03:23.531
and not be so judgmental and will accept me

90
00:03:23.531 --> 00:03:25.801
as their family.

91
00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.070
<v ->So you went through these very painful beginning years,</v>

92
00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:32.214
in your teenage years of self-discovery, isolation,

93
00:03:32.214 --> 00:03:34.174
and then you went on to do something,

94
00:03:34.174 --> 00:03:36.990
I think it would sound particularly challenging,

95
00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:38.398
you joined the military

96
00:03:38.398 --> 00:03:40.815
and you became an officer,

97
00:03:40.815 --> 00:03:42.796
and you ended up in the Pentagon.

98
00:03:42.796 --> 00:03:43.796
<v ->Right.</v>

99
00:03:43.796 --> 00:03:44.725
<v ->Then what?</v>

100
00:03:44.725 --> 00:03:47.873
This had to have only created only more isolation

101
00:03:47.873 --> 00:03:49.213
internally.

102
00:03:49.213 --> 00:03:51.217
<v ->It's one of those contradictions that many of us</v>

103
00:03:51.217 --> 00:03:52.402
have in life,

104
00:03:52.402 --> 00:03:55.175
that a young, gay teenager who feared the military

105
00:03:55.175 --> 00:03:57.670
by watching Vietnam on television through the 70s

106
00:03:57.670 --> 00:04:00.093
swore off ever joining the military.

107
00:04:00.093 --> 00:04:02.386
And I turned 18 and what did I do?

108
00:04:02.386 --> 00:04:04.401
I joined the military.

109
00:04:05.423 --> 00:04:09.724
As I said, sex was not my defining issue.

110
00:04:09.724 --> 00:04:11.147
I was Jeff,

111
00:04:11.147 --> 00:04:13.334
and I became a medic,

112
00:04:13.334 --> 00:04:16.063
and I flew medevac for about eight years in the military,

113
00:04:16.063 --> 00:04:17.343
lived in the Middle East,

114
00:04:17.343 --> 00:04:20.680
and experienced tremendous amounts of excitement and joy,

115
00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:22.906
and grief and loss.

116
00:04:22.906 --> 00:04:26.154
I was caught up in witch hunts from time to time,

117
00:04:26.154 --> 00:04:28.121
and friends of mine who were thrown out of the military

118
00:04:28.121 --> 00:04:29.275
for being gay.

119
00:04:29.275 --> 00:04:32.364
I think that added to the fear that I had been accumulating

120
00:04:32.364 --> 00:04:35.509
throughout my life, which brings us to this interview of why

121
00:04:35.509 --> 00:04:36.941
I even am here,

122
00:04:36.941 --> 00:04:38.984
is the fear that had built up.

123
00:04:38.984 --> 00:04:40.172
Fear of rejection,

124
00:04:40.172 --> 00:04:42.055
fear of the military.
<v ->Discovery.</v>

125
00:04:42.055 --> 00:04:43.950
<v ->Fear of discovery.</v>

126
00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:45.517
But I stuck with it.

127
00:04:45.517 --> 00:04:48.773
I spent 20 years in the Air Force until I retired

128
00:04:48.773 --> 00:04:51.671
the end of 2000,

129
00:04:51.671 --> 00:04:52.886
from the Pentagon,

130
00:04:52.886 --> 00:04:54.545
my last assignment was

131
00:04:54.545 --> 00:04:58.048
in the Directorate for Strategic Planning for the Air Force.

132
00:04:58.048 --> 00:05:01.264
I was a major and I finally called it quits.

133
00:05:01.264 --> 00:05:04.119
<v ->Let's talk about that for Strategic Planning.</v>

134
00:05:04.119 --> 00:05:07.679
Fear was your big issue in life, fear.

135
00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:10.887
Just encased in fear which was creating isolation,

136
00:05:10.887 --> 00:05:12.323
deep, deep depression,

137
00:05:12.323 --> 00:05:16.206
and a need for escape, a desire to escape.

138
00:05:17.217 --> 00:05:19.473
You drew to you

139
00:05:20.199 --> 00:05:23.586
currently a very interesting position at the Pentagon

140
00:05:23.586 --> 00:05:26.527
because your job was to dream of worst-case scenarios.

141
00:05:26.527 --> 00:05:27.734
<v ->That's right.</v>

142
00:05:27.734 --> 00:05:29.987
Ironically, I discovered this more and more now

143
00:05:29.987 --> 00:05:32.280
how we do attract things into our life

144
00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:36.287
and we do create our so-called reality as we perceive it.

145
00:05:36.642 --> 00:05:39.805
I had experiencing fear many times to go to bed at night

146
00:05:39.805 --> 00:05:42.011
and I would think of all the negative scenarios that could

147
00:05:42.011 --> 00:05:43.485
possibly play out for the next day.

148
00:05:43.485 --> 00:05:45.056
Whether it was arguing with my boss,

149
00:05:45.056 --> 00:05:47.357
or having a relationship go sour,

150
00:05:47.357 --> 00:05:49.117
or this problem, that problem.

151
00:05:49.117 --> 00:05:50.818
You'd work yourself up into a frenzy

152
00:05:50.818 --> 00:05:52.273
and your muscles would become tense

153
00:05:52.273 --> 00:05:53.680
and you become excited,

154
00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:55.265
and you realize, wait a minute, stop.

155
00:05:55.265 --> 00:05:57.945
It's just a scenario that you've dreamt.

156
00:05:57.945 --> 00:06:01.223
And ironically, I believe that I attracted to myself

157
00:06:01.223 --> 00:06:03.276
the position at the Pentagon in Strategic Planning

158
00:06:03.276 --> 00:06:06.045
where part of the job was to dream up scenarios,

159
00:06:06.045 --> 00:06:09.094
what could possibly go wrong and could we plan

160
00:06:09.094 --> 00:06:11.761
to avoid that and to thwart these problems

161
00:06:11.771 --> 00:06:14.074
that would affect the military.

162
00:06:15.615 --> 00:06:17.226
I didn't realize it till after I left there,

163
00:06:17.226 --> 00:06:18.575
that my goodness,

164
00:06:18.575 --> 00:06:21.297
I brought on myself because I've become so good

165
00:06:21.297 --> 00:06:24.466
at dreaming up of all the negative possibilities.

166
00:06:24.466 --> 00:06:26.687
<v ->And every one of them encased in fear,</v>

167
00:06:26.687 --> 00:06:28.099
again, always going back to fear.

168
00:06:28.099 --> 00:06:31.468
So, you left the military along the way,

169
00:06:31.468 --> 00:06:34.014
because you weren't married, living the traditional life,

170
00:06:34.014 --> 00:06:35.962
you had always wanted to be a dad,

171
00:06:35.962 --> 00:06:39.398
and you ended up getting in the foster care system

172
00:06:39.398 --> 00:06:43.216
with some pretty troubled young men.

173
00:06:43.216 --> 00:06:45.996
Can you talk about what happened

174
00:06:45.996 --> 00:06:50.033
and maybe even up through what happened with Ryan,

175
00:06:50.033 --> 00:06:51.749
after you began taking,

176
00:06:51.749 --> 00:06:52.887
yeah, let's talk about that.

177
00:06:52.887 --> 00:06:54.236
'Cause this really all starts playing in

178
00:06:54.236 --> 00:06:55.596
to what's happening now.

179
00:06:55.596 --> 00:06:58.020
<v ->I think too, going back to when I was around 21,</v>

180
00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:00.646
the seeds of this genesis come from

181
00:07:00.646 --> 00:07:02.713
I had a boyfriend who died of a drug overdose

182
00:07:02.713 --> 00:07:05.496
on his 21st birthday, his name was Jeff also.

183
00:07:05.496 --> 00:07:07.197
Of course I had to grieve this internally

184
00:07:07.197 --> 00:07:08.417
and couldn't let anyone know about it,

185
00:07:08.417 --> 00:07:10.282
but I knew that so many young people,

186
00:07:10.282 --> 00:07:12.313
especially young, gay men get caught up in drugs

187
00:07:12.313 --> 00:07:13.762
because there's so much pain.

188
00:07:13.762 --> 00:07:16.015
And I think that sometimes they track that to themselves

189
00:07:16.015 --> 00:07:19.207
to alleviate the pain, and the suffering

190
00:07:19.207 --> 00:07:21.887
that society doles out.

191
00:07:22.527 --> 00:07:24.265
When I retired from the Air Force,

192
00:07:24.265 --> 00:07:28.371
I decided two months after 9/11 after seeing the smoke go up

193
00:07:28.371 --> 00:07:30.671
over my old place of employment,

194
00:07:30.671 --> 00:07:33.381
I thought it's time to get out of town and take my kids.

195
00:07:33.381 --> 00:07:36.562
So I moved to Phoenix, Arizona with no friends or family,

196
00:07:36.562 --> 00:07:39.762
and I thought, okay we're gonna start out fresh.

197
00:07:39.762 --> 00:07:41.462
Boy, it's been the worst

198
00:07:41.462 --> 00:07:43.036
five years of my life,
(chuckling)

199
00:07:43.036 --> 00:07:45.434
the most difficult five years of my life.

200
00:07:45.969 --> 00:07:49.465
My eldest son who I had adopted when I was at the Pentagon,

201
00:07:49.465 --> 00:07:51.415
<v ->Just when you thought things couldn't get worse, right?</v>

202
00:07:51.415 --> 00:07:53.066
<v ->He required hospitalization,</v>

203
00:07:53.066 --> 00:07:54.919
he'd suffered from bipolar disorder

204
00:07:54.919 --> 00:07:57.969
from post traumatic stress disorder, depression,

205
